Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T1]: Understanding SPF: Email Authentication Protocol

SPF - Sender Policy Framework

SPF is an email authentication protocol that allows the domain owner to specify which mail servers are authorized to send emails for that domain. This list is published as a DNS TXT record for that domain. It also allows the receiving mail server to check during mail delivery that the received mail was sent from a mail server authorized by the sending domain's administrators.


Lets elaborate. Each organization has its mail server (or servers) to send and receive emails. They can be in-house servers or servers owned by an external service provider. For example, we at CyberDefenders use Google as an email service provider instead of hosting our mail servers. By doing so, we are using Google mail servers to send and receive emails for cyberdefenders.org. 


That means that other organizations should expect all incoming emails from any-thing-here@cyberdefenders.org to be sent from one of Google's mail servers. It also means for other organizations that any incoming email from @cyberdefenders.org that did not originate from Google mail servers should be treated as spoofed.

 

The SPF record for an organization tells the world two things:

  1. List of authorized sending email servers.
  2. What action to take upon receiving an email from a server, not on the allowed list?
     

Lets take a look at a live example. We can check the SPF record for any domain by checking DNS TXT records. We can do this by executing: 


dig <domain> TXT | grep spf

For example, to check the SPF record of cyberdefenders.org, we will run the following command

dig cyberdefenders.org TXT | grep spf

Figure - zoom in


Let's break it down:

  • V=spf1 - - - > SPF Protocol version.
  • include:_spf.google.com - - - > Telling the world that cyberdefenders.org authorized sending mail servers are listed in another TXT record. If we query the TXT record "_spf.google.com", we will see that it translates to "v=spf1 include:_netblocks.google.com include:_netblocks2.google.com include:_netblocks3.google.com ~all".
  • As shown in the image above, three different TXT records are included under "_spf.google.com". Checking any of them will show the actual IPs of authorized sending mail servers for cyberdefenders.org.
  • -all - - - > the action to take by the receiving mail server in case an unauthorized server sent the email (e.g., not listed in the SPF record of cyberdefenders.org). In our case, we tell the receiving organization to flag this mail as SPF FAIL.

An SPF record has two main components; mechanisms and qualifiers. Mechanisms represent the IPs being matched and are prefixed with Qualifiers that state what action should be taken if that mechanism (i.e., IP address) is matched. We can think of mechanisms as different ways to include IPs in the SPF record. The following table summarizes popular mechanism and their meanings:
 

Mechanism

Example SPF Record

Explanation

ip4

v=spf1 ip4:10.0.0.1/24

Authorized server IPs are in the 10.0.0.1/24 range

a

v=spf1 a:example.com

Authorized servers' IPs are in the DNS A record of example.com

mx

v=spf1 mx:example.com

Authorized servers IPs are the IPs of the servers in the DNS MX record of example.com

Include

v=spf1 include:_spf.domain.com

Authorized servers' IPs are in another SPF/TXT record (_spf.domain.com in that case)

all

v=spf1 all

Authorized servers' IPs match any IP.


Each of the above mechanisms should be prefixed with a qualifier to state the action upon matching the provided IP. The following table summarizes available qualifiers and their meaning:

 

Qualifier

Example SPF Record

Explanation

Action

+ (pass)

v=spf1 +ip4:10.0.0.1/24

Pass SPF check If the sender server IP is in the 10.0.0.1/24 range

Accept the message (This is an authentic message)

- (fail)

v=spf1 -ip4:10.0.0.1/24

Fail SPF check If the sender server IP is in the 10.0.0.1/24 range

Reject the message (This is a spoofed message)

~ (softfail)

v=spf1 ~ip4:10.0.0.1/24

SoftFail SPF checks If the sender server IP is in the 10.0.0.1/24 range

Accept the message but flag it as spam or junk (probably a spoofed message).

? (neutral)

v=spf1 ?ip4:10.0.0.1/24

Neither pass nor fail If the sender server IP is in the 10.0.0.1/24 range

Accept the message (Not sure whether this is a spoofed or authentic message)

The default qualifier is + (i.e., Pass), and using it or leaving the mechanism without a qualifier has the same impact. Meaning

 v=spf1 +ip4:10.0.0.1/24
 
is the same as
v=spf1 ip4:10.0.0.1/24

SPF records are evaluated left to right within the record. Matching a mechanism group triggers the corresponding qualifier action, and the evaluation stops at this point (i.e., other remaining mechanism groups will not be evaluated).
 

For example, imagine having the following SPF record v=spf1 +ip4:10.0.0.10 ~a:example.com -all. We have three mechanisms and their corresponding qualifiers. Consider the following scenarios:

  • If the sender server IP address is 10.0.0.10, the first mechanism will hit and match, SPF evaluates to pass, and the evaluation stops at this point.
  • If the sender server IP address is in the A record of example.com, the first mechanism will hit but not match; the second mechanism will hit and match, SPF evaluates to SoftFail, and the evaluation stops at this point.
  • If the sender server IP address is anything other than 10.0.0.10 and the IP address in the A record of example.com, the first two mechanisms will hit but not match. The third mechanism will hit and match, and SPF evaluates to Fail.

 

The all mechanism is always used at the end of the SPF record as a catch-all rule for anything that does not match the leading mechanisms. Think of it like the Block All rule you add to the end of your firewall policy to block anything you have not explicitly allowed.

 

SPF includes two parties, the sender -who creates the SPF record- and the recipient -who validates the SPF record. We have seen how senders can create SPF records, but what about recipients? Looking at Cisco Email Security Appliance, one of the most popular SEGs,  an SPF record evaluation process can have any of the following results:

To get this view, browse to Mail policies->Incoming content filters-> add filter->add condition. Without spending too much-explaining configurations, CISCO ESA works simply by creating policies, assigning filters to policies, and defining filter condition(s) and action(s).


As we can see in the screenshot above, the Cisco ESA offers the following checks to perform against incoming emails: 

Result

Explanation

None

There is no SPF record

Pass

The sender's IP is authorized to send emails.

Neutral

The sender's IP is neither authorized nor unauthorized to send emails. It usually happens when the sender's IP does not match any mechanism in the SPF record. For example, an SPF record like v=spf1 will always evaluate to neutral.

SoftFail

The sender IP is not authorized at the moment

Fail

The sender's IP is not authorized to send emails.

TempError

Temporary error while grabbing SPF record (i.e., DNS query timeout)

PermError

Permeant error while grabbing SPF record (i.e., misformatted SPF record)

 

Note: You can download the Cisco email security appliance from here and use this video to guide you through the deployment process.
 

Another thing domain owners should pay attention to is the maximum limit of DNS queries for an SPF record. The SPF specification limits the number of DNS lookups to 10. This limit helps reduce the number of resources mailbox providers use when checking SPF records. So, keeping the SPF record simple is highly recommended, and using the ipv4 mechanism whenever possible. Otherwise, SPF will fail if it requires more than 10 DNS queries to expand.

Let's have a look at a complete end-to-end scenario to explain what's happening under the hood for both sending and receiving parties:

 

Figure - zoom in


  1. Receiving company mail server receives an email from omar@sender-company.com directed to oways@receiving-company.com.
  2. If the SPF check is activated on mail.receiving-company.com incoming mail gateway, it will check sender-company.com DNS server for the existence of an SPF record.
  3. Mail.receiving-company.com grabs the list of authorized email servers for sender-company.com.
  4. Mail.receiving-company.com compares the source IP of the mail server that sent the email (1.1.1.1 in our example) to the list of authorized servers.
  5. If the IP is authorized, the SPF check will pass, and mail.receiving-company.com will deliver the mail to oways@receiving-company.com inbox.
  6. If the SPF evaluation does not PASS, mail.receiving-company.com mail server will check the action listed in the SPF record and act accordingly.

Notes:

  • Sending and receiving emails are independent functions. Organizations can have servers dedicated to sending emails and others for receiving emails. Google is a live example that dedicates five servers for receiving emails and has a bunch of other servers for sending emails. Receiving mail servers are listed in the DNS MX record of that domain.
  • Generally speaking, SPF records can contain IP addresses, CIDR ranges, additional TXT records, or a combination of them. Check Twitter SPF record using MXToolBox, and you will see a mix of IPs, CIDR ranges, and additional TXT records in a single SPF record.


Steps to implement SPF:

  1. Determine the domain your organization uses to send emails from.
  2. Collect IP addresses of your organization's authorized outgoing/sending mail servers.
  3. Create your SPF record manually or use online tools such as spfwizard.net.
  4. Publish your SPF record as a TXT record on your organization's DNS server.
  5. Test your published SPF record.

 

Each organization is responsible for activating SPF verification for received emails on their incoming mail gateway. SPF will be useless if the receiving organization does not verify SPF for incoming emails. It's also important to note that the action specified in the SPF can be overridden, and it's up to the recipient mail server to determine what action to take. For example, if the action in the SPF record is 'FAIL', the recipient organization can accept the message instead of dropping it.

Here is how to activate SPF verification on Cisco ESA. To get this view, browse to Mail policies->mail flow policies and select the 'accepted' policy.

Figure - zoom in


As we can see, the receiving party can switch on/off SPF verification for incoming emails regardless of how SPF policy is configured by the sending party.
